{"query": "Which vegetation management practices are most likely to benefit amphibian populations, and which are likely to be ineffective or harmful?", "summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, several vegetation management practices show potential benefits for amphibian populations. Managing grazing regimes (Action 780) showed mixed results, with one study finding grazed plots did not have higher natterjack toad abundance and had lower common toad abundance, while five studies found that habitat management including grazing reintroduction increased green toad populations and maintained or increased natterjack and common toad populations. Changing mowing regimes (Action 783) showed promise, with one study finding that restoration including reduced mowing increased numbers of frog species. Managing ditches (Action 749) demonstrated benefits, with one study showing increased common toad numbers and another finding significantly higher amphibian species numbers and abundance in ditches managed under agri-environment schemes compared to conventional management.

Prescribed fire practices (Action 877) showed variable results across 14 studies - eight found no effect on amphibian abundance or species numbers, four found mixed effects depending on species and burn timing, three found increased abundance or species numbers, and one found decreased abundance. Time since prescribed fires also showed mixed results with both increases and decreases in amphibian measures.

Some practices have limited evidence. Managing cutting regimes (Action 788) and silviculture practices in plantations (Action 792) lacked specific studies in the available evidence. For invasive plant control (Action 3697), studies focused primarily on reptiles rather than amphibians, and encouraging aquatic plant growth (Action 796) had no available evidence for effects on amphibian populations.", "action_ids": ["780","783","749","877","788","792","3697","796"]}

