{"query": "How effective are conservation actions such as legal protection, habitat creation, and translocation for great crested newt populations in the UK?", "summary": "Based on studies from the UK, conservation actions for great crested newts show mixed effectiveness. For translocation, four of six studies found that translocated great crested newts maintained or established breeding populations (Action 858). However, one systematic review of 31 great crested newt studies found no conclusive evidence that mitigation including translocations resulted in self-sustaining populations (Action 858). Populations were present one year after release in 37% of cases, and one study found that within three years breeding failed in 48% of ponds despite initial success (Action 858). Great crested newts reproduced following 56% of translocations (Action 858).

For habitat creation, three before-and-after studies found that great crested newts established breeding populations at 57-75% of created ponds (Action 863). Three replicated studies found that up to 88% of created ponds were colonized by translocated or naturally colonizing great crested newts (Action 863). Head-started great crested newts reproduced in 38% of created ponds (Action 863). However, one systematic review found no conclusive evidence that mitigation which often included pond creation resulted in self-sustaining populations (Action 863). One study found that providing artificial hibernacula along with other terrestrial habitat management maintained populations of great crested newts (Action 759), though created hibernacula were not used by great crested newts in another study (Action 759). Creating refugia for great crested newts along with other interventions maintained four populations (Action 772). Pond deepening and enlarging resulted in establishment of a breeding population of great crested newts (Action 817).

For legal protection, three reviews found that legal protection of amphibian species was not effective at protecting populations during development (Action 779). However, the number of great crested newt mitigation licences issued over 10 years increased to over 600 in England and Wales (Action 779).", "action_ids": ["858","863","779","759","772","817"]}

